content:
Creating an interactive quiz using HTML and JavaScript is a great way to practice web development skills. Below, I'll provide a simple example of how you can structure your HTML and JavaScript to create a quiz with three questions, track the user's score, and display the results at the end.

### HTML Structure

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Interactive Quiz</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            margin: 20px;
        }
        .question {
            margin-bottom: 20px;
        }
        .result {
            font-weight: bold;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Interactive Quiz</h1>
    <div id="quiz-container">
        <div class="question" data-correct="b">
            <p>1. What is the capital of France?</p>
            <input type="radio" name="q1" value="a"> Berlin<br>
            <input type="radio" name="q1" value="b"> Paris<br>
            <input type="radio" name="q1" value="c"> Madrid<br>
        </div>
        <div class="question" data-correct="a">
            <p>2. What is 2 + 2?</p>
            <input type="radio" name="q2" value="a"> 4<br>
            <input type="radio" name="q2" value="b"> 3<br>
            <input type="radio" name="q2" value="c"> 5<br>
        </div>
        <div class="question" data-correct="c">
            <p>3. Which planet is known as the Red Planet?</p>
            <input type="radio" name="q3" value="a"> Earth<br>
            <input type="radio" name="q3" value="b"> Jupiter<br>
            <input type="radio" name="q3" value="c"> Mars<br>
        </div>
        <button onclick="checkAnswers()">Submit</button>
    </div>
    <div id="result" class="result"></div>

    <script src="quiz.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

### JavaScript Code (quiz.js)

```javascript
function checkAnswers() {
    const questions = document.querySelectorAll('.question');
    let score = 0;

    questions.forEach(question => {
        const correctAnswer = question.dataset.correct;
        const selectedAnswer = question.querySelector('input[type="radio"]:checked');

        if (selectedAnswer && selectedAnswer.value === correctAnswer) {
            score++;
        }
    });

    displayResult(score, questions.length);
}

function displayResult(score, totalQuestions) {
    const resultContainer = document.getElementById('result');
    resultContainer.innerHTML = `You scored ${score} out of ${totalQuestions}.`;

    if (score === totalQuestions) {
        resultContainer.innerHTML += " Perfect score! Well done!";
    }
}
```

### Explanation

1. **HTML Structure**: 
   - Each question is wrapped in a `div` with a `data-correct` attribute indicating the correct answer.
   - Radio buttons are used for answer selection, and each question has a unique name attribute to ensure only one option can be selected per question.

2. **JavaScript**:
   - The `checkAnswers` function iterates over each question, checks the selected answer against the correct answer, and updates the score accordingly.
   - The `displayResult` function displays the user's score and a message based on their performance.

3. **Styling**:
   - Basic CSS is used to style the quiz for a simple and clean appearance.

You can enhance this code further by adding more questions, improving styling, or adding features like a timer or feedback for each question. This example provides a solid foundation for creating an interactive quiz using HTML and JavaScript.
